Part 1: Data

The survey was conducted by questionaire. The populations in the survey is people in United States. Becuase the questions in the survey is asking for the opinions of people, the varibles are categorical variables. There are 57061 observations and 114 variables in the dataset. The data was collected by romdom smapling and quesitons. Therefore, it can only answer the generalizability of an inference.

Part 2: Research question

My first question is what proportion of American in 1972 would report that they are Catholic?. One will be interested in this question becuase the result would be a important indicator that shows the religious change of American. Analayzing the results, historians can see the trend of religion in historical view.

My second question is In 1972, is there a difference between the proportion of female who believe in Cathoic and the proportion of male? The result of this question will answer more sepcific quesitons to historian who are interested in the religious change.

My third question isIn 1972, is there a difference between the proportion of female who earned above avarage income and the proportion of male? The result of the question can build a more specific social demographic of people in 1972. It will help historians what might cause the religious change even though my quesiton only answer the associaiton of variables but not the causality.

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

The code here made a new table that ontains only the data recorded at 1972 and has four variables(year, sex, religious status, Cathoic/Non-Catholic)

Religious<-gss%>%
  filter(relig!= "NA", year=="1972")%>%
  select(year,sex, relig)
Religious<-Religious%>%
  mutate(True_false= ifelse(relig=="Catholic", yes="Catholic", no="Non-Catholic"))

This histogram describes the spread of religion in 1972

ggplot(data = Religious, aes(x= relig))+geom_bar()

There are more poeple who reported religon other than Catholic.

ggplot(data = Religious, aes(x= True_false))+geom_bar()

The number of male and female are almost the same.

ggplot(data = Religious, aes(x= sex))+geom_bar()

The code made a new table that contains only the data from 1972 and has four variables(Year, sex, Income status, Above Average/Not-Above Average)

Income_status<-gss%>%

Income_status<-Income_status%>%
  mutate(Above_avg= ifelse(incom16=="Above Average", yes="Above Average", no="Non-Above Average"))

Part 4: Inference

Hypotheses: the popluationn proportion will state same as the proportion of sample. Check: Independt, np>10%, (1-p)n>10% Method: Theoretical becuase the sample proportion is known.

413/1608
## [1] 0.2568408
1195/1608
## [1] 0.7431592
inference(y=True_false, data = Religious, type = "ci", statistic = "proportion", success = "Catholic", method = "theoretical" )
## Single categorical variable, success: Catholic
## n = 1608, p-hat = 0.2568
## 95% CI: (0.2355 , 0.2782)

Accroding to the reslut, we are 95% confident that the proportion of Catholic in 1972 is between23.5% and 27.8%

Hypotheses: Null: There is not differece, Alternative: there is a difference. Check: Independent, np>10%, (1-p)n>10% Method: Theoretical- the proportion of Female and Male can be compared to each other

inference(y=True_false, x= sex, data = Religious, type = "ht", statistic = "proportion", null = 0, alternative = "twosided",success ="Catholic", method = "theoretical" )
## Response variable: categorical (2 levels, success: Catholic)
## Explanatory variable: categorical (2 levels) 
## n_Male = 804, p_hat_Male = 0.2724
## n_Female = 804, p_hat_Female = 0.2413
## H0: p_Male =  p_Female
## HA: p_Male != p_Female
## z = 1.427
## p_value = 0.1536

Accroding to the result, there is no strong evidence that indicate there is a difference between the proportion of female and male. So, we cannot refuse the Null hypothesis.

Hypotheses: Null: There is not differece, Alternative: there is a difference. Check: Independent, np>10%, (1-p)n>10% Method: Theoretical- the proportion of Female and Male can be compared to each other

Income_status<-gss%>%
  filter(incom16!= "NA", year=="1972")%>%
  select(year,sex, incom16)
Income_status<-Income_status%>%
  mutate(Above_avg= ifelse(incom16=="Above Average", yes="Above Average", no="Non-Above Average"))

inference(y=Above_avg, x= sex, data = Income_status, type = "ht", statistic = "proportion", null = 0, alternative = "twosided",success ="Above Average", method = "theoretical")
## Response variable: categorical (2 levels, success: Above Average)
## Explanatory variable: categorical (2 levels) 
## n_Male = 801, p_hat_Male = 0.1036
## n_Female = 792, p_hat_Female = 0.1048
## H0: p_Male =  p_Female
## HA: p_Male != p_Female
## z = -0.0769
## p_value = 0.9387

Accroding to the result, there is no strong evidence that indicate there is a difference between the proportion of female and male. So, we cannot refuse the Null hypothesis.
